\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
Sure!  Yeah, I was born in 1925, in a small town in Lancashire, called Oldham, where I grew up, and as I grew up my sole ambition was to be, to join the RAF, to fly.  I\rquote d no conception of social science, or ever becoming anything like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 So what 
was your family background, then?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9705458 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 Well, my father had been in the First World War, and after he got out he became a policeman.  He was the Chief of the D}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9705458 etective Bureau in this town.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 And I left school relatively early, because I wanted to - as I
 said, my ambition was to fly.  And I went to work at a factory making aircraft instruments, and did electrical engineering, like one day a week, and two nights a week.  And I was in the Air Training Corps.  And I was then selected for a university short 
course, by the RAF, and went to Cambridge in ... I guess that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9705458  was in the beginning of 1943.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
Then I was in the RAF for five years, ... I went to Rhodesia for flying training, and then came back, just as the War ended!  I finished just in time to miss the ac
tion, though during the earlier period, before we got to go overseas, I spent quite a lot of time hanging around on various airfields, waiting to go on a troop ship to South Africa.  And then after the War ended, I went back to England, and \'85
 I was commissioned, and on various training cou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9705458 rses, and flying assignments.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
And then, one day, somebody came along and asked if anybody was familiar with German.  I had done some German at school, I couldn\rquote t say I could really speak it, so, not knowing anything, and ignoring the injunction, \'93Never volunteer for anything
\'94, I said \'93Yes\'94!  And I was selected to go to Germany on an operation called, \'93The Missing Research and Enquiry Service\'94, to find out what had happened to RAF air crews that had been shot down over Germ
any.  And the idea was to try to discover, if they had been listed as missing but not known what had happened, to find out if they\rquote d been shot by the SS, or whatever.  So \'85
 I went, first of all, to Denmark, and then to Northern Germany, and then to the American Zone of Germany, near Frankfurt, and then to Heidelberg, and then to Paris.  So I got a fairly good idea of  \'85
 of a Europe that I had not known before.  I mean, it was a devastated Europe, this was just after the War ended.  Then I didn\rquote t quite know 
what to do after that.  I went back to Cambridge and talked to the Senior Tutor at my College, and I told him I didn\rquote t want to do economics, which I\rquote d done when I was there before.  And he said, \'93What about this \'85
 new-fangled subject called anthropology?\'94  So I said, \'93Really?\'94  I\rquote 
d actually thought of doing history, because when I was there during the War, Herbert Butterfield was lecturing, and that was quite influential on me.  As well as the Tutor in Pembroke, who was a man called Wilfred Knox, who was on
e of the famous, or infamous, Knox Brothers!  So I said, \'93Well, why not?\'94
 you know.  So I did.  And I had absolutely no intention, or idea, of becoming a professional academic.  I mean, nothing could have been further from my mind!  But, having got a First in both parts of the Tripos, it was very difficult not to do!
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15480958 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
