ve discussed some of this, I think, on my website.  And I went, I travelled around with various government officers, like the Co-operatives Officer, and so they\rquote 
d take me to various places.  And Hope Town, everybody said Hope Town is the most backward village in the country, people don\rquote t pay their rates, they are
 very African, and this, and that, and the other!  So I went there one day, the Co-ops Officer dropped me off in the middle of the village about ten o\rquote clock in the morning, and I walked along to \'85
 I asked somebody where I could find the Village Chairman, and they said, \'93Oh, he\rquote s away in England.  But the Village Office is up there\'94
.  So I went there, and there was a group of men, including the overseer, who subsequently became a great friend of mine.  A few, you know, men who were sitting around.  And they 
started talking.  I tried to explain to them what I was interested in, and they said, \'93Oh yes.  This is the place!\'94  And they took me off to the Chinese store-keeper, and said, \'93Oh yes, we can find you a house to live, and we\rquote 
