So how did you manage, in a practical way, then?  Did you have some help from people?  Or did you cook for yourself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 Oh, \'85
 I had a cook.  She sort of despaired of me, because I was so difficult with food!  I mean, I\rquote ve got a lot of food!  I used to order from Booker\rquote s in Georgetown, and it would be sent down by train, like baked beans and \'85
 (LAUGHS)  But, yes, I mean, she cooked things like local fish and so forth.  But there were a lot of local things that I did not eat, and could not eat.  Yes, she was the sister of Jimmy Johnson, the Village Overseer. \'85
 And there were a whole lot of people used to come all the time.  And there was an agricultural instructor in the village, who was from Georgetown, who helped me plant a kitchen garden, for example.  Kids used to come all the time, and we\rquote 
d make ice cream, and the kids would eat it!  There was a lot of social life, dances and so forth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
And you made friends?
