\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
Oh yes, yes.  A lot.  By the time I left, I knew everybody in the village.  The village had a population of about 1,800, and I knew virtually everybody, and had been to everybody\rquote 
s house.  I collected quite a lot of the information myself, but I also had people who helped to collect basic sort of census information, and \'85 and the land tenure information, I got a lot of it from the Village Overseer, who kept all the land r
ecords.  And the Lands and Mines Department, at that time, was extremely good.  They had cadastral surveys of every village.  These villages were old plantations.  You know, the whole coast of Guyana is divided into long, parallel strips, with the short e
n
d at the sea, and the other end up at the water conservancy at the back, and they had detailed maps that I got from them.  And they did surveys, periodically, in order to sort out the way in which land had been transmitted in between the surveys, and it w
as transmitted in all kinds of very complicated ways, you know, which was part of the interest of the thing.
