\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid555335 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 Well, yes.  Yes, Jamaica is very different, because \'85
 the system in Jamaica is really an old English system of land, where every time land is transferred, you do a survey, and you try to keep up with that.  Whereas, since these coastlands had been Dutch, and were, i
n fact, brought under cultivation in the middle of the 18}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
 century, by the Dutch, they operated with Roman Dutch Law on landholding.  And after the British came, they began to do cadastral surveys fairly early on.  So every plantation had been surveyed, a
nd when it was bought by groups of ex-slaves, as they were, after slavery had ended, a lot of plantations went bankrupt.  The system of water control was essential, if they were to be cultivated.  Unfortunately, a lot of the water control system broke dow
n, and if you went along the coast where Hope Town was, the West Coast of Berbice, you\rquote 
d see lots of villages actually under water for most of the year, because the sea defences were not kept up.  The government did not have comprehensive sea defence system
s at that time.  Each village was supposed to maintain, clear out its own drainage canals, and maintain its back dams, so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid555335  that water wouldn\rquote t come in.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 But, you know, it was difficult.  After slavery ended, when these groups of ex-slaves bought these plant
ations, they immediately began to cultivate them in crops like arrowroot, which was an export crop, and other crops.  But they were driven out by the power of the planter class, who wanted them to go back to work in the surviving sugar plantations.  So it
 was very difficult for them.  They had to work in order to get money to live the way they wanted to live, and cultivation was very difficult.  They had to \'85
 the Central Government organised them into villages, and tried to get them to pay rates and so forth, and most of them didn\rquote 
t have money, so they paid rates in the form of labour.  They would contribute labour to the maintenance of the water control system, which sometimes worked and sometimes didn\rquote t.  And so that, I mean, it\rquote s true that, in a general s
ense, because of the necessity for water control, sea defence, and irrigation and drainage, you had some sort of central control.  But it\rquote 
s not until relatively recently that you had a comprehensive system of water control.  The sugar estates, of course, they operated their water control systems extremely well, and during the 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\super\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958  century they began to consolidate \'85 from hundreds of small plantations, you ended up with, I don\rquote 
t know, less than 20 big ones.  Most of them owned by the Bookers.
