\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
Well, they did, yes.  But they didn\rquote t call it family }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid555335 land.  What happened was, if \'85 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
when the original plantation was bought, take Hope Town, for example.  In 1840, the biggest section of Hope Town was bought by a group of ex-slaves.  I have the document in the book.  And they divided it up into shares, among \'85 I don\rquote 
t know, 30 families.  And you\rquote d get one house lot at the front, by the sea, and you\rquote d get some cultivation land in what they called the \'93first depth\'94
, which was not too far, and then some in the next depth, and so forth.  Over time, those lands would be inherited, and under Roman Dutch Law, you could inherit them, jointly, without any dividing line in the property \endash  legally.  And they call it 
\'93children\rquote s property\'94, \'85 not family land.  It\rquote s a different concept to the Jamaican one.  But, in effect, it\rquote 
s very much the same.  But, periodically, the government would come along and do a survey, and try to sort out individual ownership.  But many pieces of land remained as children\rquote s property.  So you\rquote d have \'85
 several people would actually own the title.  But the native concept, so to speak, was that anybody born in the village could be given a place to live.  They were very reluctant to alienate any
 land to outsiders.  So if a man married into the village, he would not get the land in his name, it would stay in his wife\rquote s name. \'85  So a lot of that was, was discussed in the original book.
