Yeah, they are from that early period.  But most of the information was kept on these big cards, and separate information on land tenure \endash  who owned land, who was working it, whether it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid555335 
was under cultivation or not.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
The interesting thing is that the African American population was not terribly oriented toward agricultural activity.  What they did was, they worked on the sugar plantations for money, during the s
eason, and they planted vegetable crops, mainly for domestic consumption or local sales.  So you\rquote 
d have, you know, mixed crop beds in various places.  People would grow yams and and corn, and other things.  The East Indians, on the other hand, when they mo
ved off the plantations, and set up independent villages, they, immediately, began to grow rice, \'85
 or raised cattle.  And if you look from the air, I have an aerial map, actually, an aerial photograph, which shows Den Amstel, which is the third village I w
orked in, and Windsor Forest, side by side, you see Windsor Forest is beautifully cultivated, and Den Amstel is mostly under bush.  But the African population would not sell land to Indians, you know.  They regarded this, \'85
 the ancient land their forefathers had bought, as sacrosanct.  And it\rquote s only recently that they began \'85 There were a few people cultivating rice in what they called the \'93first depth\'94, just behind the village, when I was there, but it
\rquote s only recently that the African Guyanese population h
as gone into rice cultivation, and then not on anything like the scale that the Indians have.  So the importance of land to people was really not so much economic as, as social and cultural.  They had a burial ground there, and all the ancestors were ther
e, and so forth.
