\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1527124 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 Well, \'85
 I think, the Indians who came from India, as indentured labour, they came on contracts for a number of years, and they were entitled to return passage.
  When their contract was up, it was in the interests of the planters to encourage them to stay, and they began to give them land on which to plant rice, irrigated land, on parts of the plantation.  And that gradually escalated.  If you take Windsor Fores
t
, for example, it had been a sugar plantation, with a resident East Indian population.  It went bankrupt, and the land was seized by the Crown, for failure to pay drainage and water control rates, and so forth, and the resident population was just abandon
ed.  They began by reaping the rattan canes, and selling sugar cane.  But you know, growing sugar cane is not as easy as growing rice.  Furthermore, they had a tradition of rice cultivation.  Not that Africans didn\rquote t grow rice, they did \'85
 even way back during the slavery period, just as they cultivated rice in South Carolina.  But the Indians also had a family structure that was conducive to working rice land.  It was extremely patriarchal.  The women and children could be put \'85
 to work in the fields, transplanting rice, all very intensive rice cultivation.  The Africans, when the African population grew rice, they never grew it in the same intensive way that Indians did.  They would broadcast \'85
 that is, they would scatter seed.  They would never plant seedlings, and then hand transplant them, which had to be done by females.  So there was a different \'85
 many reasons for the difference, including the whole tradition of slavery, and people wishing to escape from agricultural labour of that kind, regimented agricultural labour.
