But, at the end, when Sinclair Drake finally left, and I was appointed to the Chair, Nkrumah had decided, some time before, that he wanted to nationalise the University, a move that most of the people in the University agreed with, and he appo
inted an International Commission to advise on how this should be done, and they came and advised. A large Commission.  And he ignored their recommendations.  Their main recommendation was that whatever they did, they should try to maintain continuity, ke
e
p appointment contracts in place, and so forth.  He immediately, by Act of Parliament, fired four or five Faculty members, including the most senior Ghanaian, who was the Registrar.  And the students protested, there was a big student demonstration, they 
m
arched, they were going to march to Accra from Lagon, which is some miles out.  They were met at the gates of the University by, first, police, and behind them, troops, and behind them, armoured cars!  And turned back.  And it was, it was a pointless and 
