\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
No.  On the contrary, in Ghana, the matrilineal system does not marginalise men at all.  That\rquote s the argument of mine from the Caribbean.  But in Ghana, where you have matrilineal descent, the men inherit through \'85
 the relationship is between a man and his sister.  So a man\rquote s heir is his sister\rquote s son, but not his sister.  His sister\rquote 
s son.  So power and property passes from men, through the intermediary of women belonging to the matrilinear.  And, in fact, in Ghana, the men sit around, you know, drinking beer, and \'85 talking, and judging, and politicking, while th
e women do all the work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
Did you find it illuminating, for your Caribbean work, to do these studies in Africa?
\par 
