But one of the arguments I made was that the Caribbean system is not matrilineal at all, because the problem is that men don\rquote 
t have power or status.  They are, they are depressed in a hierarchical system, where power and status resides with other people.  And the interesting thing about the Indians is, they have a more hermetically sealed community.  They\rquote re not, or, at
 least at that time, they were not so oriented toward European symbols of power and success, whereas the African American population, Afro-Guianese population, their orientation was toward education, upward mobility into the Civil Service, or whatever.  T
hat was the sign of success, you know.  The Village Chairman of Hope Town was a man call T.T. Thompson, who was a big \'85 he\rquote d been Headmaster of the local school, he was a nominated member of the legislature, and Chairman of the Village Chairmen
\rquote s Conference, and so on and so forth.  And those are the people who are the symbols of success.  They also have position in the religious organisation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11600637 s, the churches and so forth.  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 Whereas in the Indian communities, the men with prestige and power are people like local mill owners, or men who have positions in the Hindu or Muslim organisations, and \'85
 they\rquote re not articulated so much, I wouldn\rquote t say not at all, because they are.  I mean, there was a degree of upward mobility and movement into the wider structures of Guianese society, but \'85
 at the local level, there are other symbols of power and success, and they\rquote re all dominated by males.  So the males have prestige and power }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 within }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 their domestic organisation.  The way that it seemed to me, at least, although it\rquote s been argued agai}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11600637 nst, that men didn
\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958  in the African population.  Not to say they\rquote re emasculated, or anything like that, but it\rquote s certainly a relative matter.
