\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8340458 Raymond:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 
First of all, there weren\rquote t really \'85 I didn\rquote t look at an important aspect of the relationship between Indian and African villages.  For example, Hope Town was \'85
 thought of itself as an African village.  It was founded by ex-slaves and so forth.  However, it had Indians living in the village.  I
t had Indian landowners on the edge of the village.  It had all kinds of relationships with a village next door, that is predominantly Indian, including intermarriage.  But those things tended to be discounted.  It\rquote 
s only when I did later work that I began to look at genealogies, and see these connections.  And, similarly, in Windsor Forest.  There are very few, what you would call, \'93mixed villages\'94
 in Guyana, and most of the mixing is in the urban areas in Georgetown and New Amsterdam.  But you go through Windsor Forest, again, it\rquote 
s an East Indian rice village.  However, there were a lot of Africans living in the village when I worked there first.  During the political conflict period, they separated out, they were driven out of the village, just as Indians
 were driven out of other places. 
