s College, and there was a dinner at which Burnham pledged his support for J
agan to move forward to independence, and so forth.  There was also a Victory Dance at a hotel on the edge of Georgetown, that I attended, where you had Indians and Africans, and Portuguese, and Chinese, and everybody you could think of, all together, cel
ebrating this electoral victory that they saw as the next step towards independence.  However, immediately that happened, the Americans, particularly Kennedy and his whole cabinet, including \'85
