  And they had all kinds of contingencies, including fomenting disturbances and strikes, which they did.  But the real instrument was to persua
de the British Government to introduce proportional representation, which would enable them, with a semblance of legitimacy, to negotiate a situation where Jagan was kept out.  But it was so cold-blooded, and unnecessary.  Absolutely unnecessary.  Jagan w
as no threat to anybo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5898761 dy, you know.  The idea that \'85 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 It\rquote 
s almost as ludicrous as that nonsensical invasion of \'85 Grenada \'85 the Americans.  Our, our what was then the Provost, he\rquote s now in the Law School, he was in the government at the time, and he would go on television and say, \'93
