Cliff Geertz, yes.  Oh, it was a great Department in those days. \'85 This Department had been greatly influenced, in the 1930s, by Radcliffe-Brown, who had been Pr
ofessor here for quite a while.  And it was regarded as a sort of outpost of British anthropology.  However, when I came here in \rquote 
66, that was not entirely the case, it was an outpost of Parsonian sociology and anthropology.  I had known Talcott Parsons for a year in Cambridge, after I went back, while I was writing my dissertation. \'85
