Systems\'94.  It was systems of society, culture and personality, at one time.  The personality tended to get dropped out, but \'85
 it was really the Parsonian paradigm that was underlying the way in which theory was taught here, for a long time.  Eventually, Marshall Sallens came here, and he had a rather different take on things.  He\rquote s a radically culture-oriented. \'85
 Schneider, Geertz, Schneider and Fallows were much more in the Parsonian tradition of trying to, trying to integrate these different points of view.  Although Clifford Geertz was much more creative in the way he took literary analogi
