\'94, \'93the family is dead\'94, and nobody knows really.  I doubt whether, \'85 in a highly individualistic society, like the United States or Europe, you\rquote 
re going to move towards that kind of recapturing of kinship solidarity.  I mean, there will be kinship solidarity, but in a limited sense.  There will be family reunions and visiting and so on and so forth, but \'85 I don\rquote t know.  It is true that
 in the South \'85
 for example, in Chicago, a lot of the people who are lower income black people, especially if they live in areas that become violent, they often send their children back to the South, to live with their grandparents, if they have them.  But
 that is going to erode over time, too. \'85  That was a phase, but I\rquote m not sure that that\rquote s going to continue.
