e average holding was like three acres or something.  There were one or two bigger rice farmers, but they were small acreages, which were cultivated intensively.  The men would plough and harrow the land, prepare it for planting, they\rquote 
d plant seed beds.  The women would transplant \'93hand stick\'94
, as they say, the rice.  And then it would be reaped.  And in Windsor Forest it was milled in small, many small mills.  There were about 18 mills, I think.  And I have a paper on the cost of production, and that kind 
of thing.  By 1975, there had been a complete transformation.  Nobody planted rice in that way.  All kinds of new varieties had been introduced.  Everybody was using tractors, there were \'85
 innumerable tractors in the village by now.  Nobody did hand transplanting.  A lot of the women had gone off to work in Georgetown, in factories of one kind or another, it\rquote 
s a fairly short journey.  And so the whole basis of the economic life of the community was changed.   What they call a \'93silo\'94, which was a sort of ric
e processing thing, had been built on the edge of the village, and all the rice was sold to the Rice Marketing Board in Georgetown, and there was no \'85  In the old days, they used to dry the rice on big concrete things in front of the mill, and they
\rquote d go around and kick it to turn it over, and so forth, and then they\rquote 
d steam it in, essentially, oil drums, with a steam generator underneath, to make parboiled rice.  And often, to thresh it, in fact, always to thresh it, they would use bulls, what they call \'93bull mashing\'94, you\rquote 
d have a post and cattle walking around and treading out the rice, which gave it its distinctive flavour of bovine urine, especially when i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16018517 t was steamed into the thing!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid15480958\charrsid15480958 None of that existed any more, it was all done in a different way, al
l done on a big mechanised basis, and the yields were higher, the income was higher.  Of course, they were using fertiliser that they had never used before.  So that changed the whole basis of the economy, and of the domestic economy.  But it didn\rquote 
t \'85 well
, at least, by that time, it had not been able to transform the internal relationships of the households to that extent.  I mean, relative independence of women was not evident.  They were working, but they were giving the money to their fathers or their 
husband.  So that was interesting.
