Yeah, leaving out people.  You see, I found in \'85 these in-depth interviews, as a rule of thumb, the first three interviews tend to be \endash  we did many interviews.  The first three i
nterviews, people tend not to talk.  But after the third interview, they begin to open up, you know, and children who had appeared as this, or that, or the other \'85
 now, we get the full story of where they actually came from, and so forth.  And people are willing to talk, once \'85 they\rquote ve established a certain kind of relationship, and they get into it.  But these one-shot interviews, I don\rquote 
t have too much faith in the accuracy of the data.
